As RISC-V increasingly gains traction across various computing domains, the need to run x86-64 applications on RISC-V platforms becomes critical. Binary translation plays a pivotal role in ensuring software portability across diverse Instruction Set Architectures (ISAs). However, the architectural differences between the widely adopted x86-64 and the emerging RISC-V platforms challenge effective translation while maintaining performance and compatibility. To address this challenge, we extend Box64 to enable efficient execution of x86-64 software on RISC-V systems. Our approach leverages a suite of both general and RISC-V-specific optimization techniques—including an innovative Total Store Ordering (TSO) emulation method, refined indirect and conditional branch optimizations, and dynamic library acceleration—to drastically reduce emulation overhead, improve execution efficiency, and maintain extensive application compatibility. Evaluations show that our solution only incurs an average performance penalty of less than 40% compared to native execution, outperforms QEMU-TCG by 3.3X, and robustly supports a wide range of applications from office suites to video games.